static.solution:
  SOLUTION 



Using the log rules, we have
\begin{aligned}
e^{0.11 t} \amp = 13 \\
\ln{ \left( e^{0.11 t} \right)} \amp = \ln{(13)} \\
0.11 t \amp = \ln{(13)} \\
t \amp = \frac{\ln{(13)}}{0.11}
\end{aligned}

  SOLUTION 



(a) \ln{AB} = \ln{ A } + \ln{ B } = x + y



(b) \begin{aligned}
\ln{(A^{4} \cdot \sqrt{B})} \amp = \ln{( A^{4})} + \ln{( \sqrt{B}) } \\
 \amp = \ln{(A^{4})} + \ln{(B^{1/2})} \\
 \amp = 4 \ \ln{A} + \frac{1}{2} \ \ln{B} \\
 \amp = 4 x + \frac{y}{2}
\end{aligned}



(c) \frac{\ln{A}}{\ln{B}} = \frac{x}{y}



(d) \ln{ \left( \frac{A}{B} \right) } = \ln{A} - \ln{B} = x-y



Since x = \ln{A} and y = \ln{B}, we can rewrite these two logarithmic equations in terms of exponents A = e^x and B = e^x respectively.  Thus:



(e) AB = e^x \cdot e^y = e^{x+y}



(f) \ln(A-B)  = \ln(e^x - e^y)

